"title": "5374: languages",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5374",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The means of communication shared in common by groups of people. Scripture teaches that the diversity of languages in the world is a result of sin, but the outpouring of the Holy Spirit in Acts broke down the barriers of language and nationality.</p>\n<h2>The origin of different languages</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen11:1-Gen11:9\">GEN 11:1–11:9</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen10:2-Gen10:5\">GEN 10:2–10:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen10:20\">GEN 10:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen10:30-Gen10:31\">GEN 10:30–10:31</a></p>\n<h2>The close relationship between language and national identity</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa19:18\">ISA 19:18</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh13:23-Neh13:27\">NEH 13:23–13:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech8:23\">ZEC 8:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev5:9\">REV 5:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev7:9\">REV 7:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev10:11\">REV 10:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev11:9\">REV 11:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev13:7\">REV 13:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:6\">REV 14:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev17:15\">REV 17:15</a></p>\n<h2>Language barriers</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh13:23-Neh13:24\">NEH 13:23–13:24</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut28:49-Deut28:50\">DEU 28:49–28:50</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps81:5\">PSA 81:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer5:15\">JER 5:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek3:5-Ezek3:6\">EZK 3:5–3:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan1:4\">DAN 1:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor14:10-1Cor14:11\">1CO 14:10–14:11</a></p>\n<h2>The diversity of languages in the Persian empire</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth8:9\">EST 8:9</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra4:7\">EZR 4:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth1:22\">EST 1:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth3:12\">EST 3:12</a></p>\n<h2>God's revelation not limited to any single language</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:1-Acts2:11\">ACT 2:1–2:11</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps19:1-Ps19:4\">PSA 19:1–19:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:44-Acts10:48\">ACT 10:44–10:48</a></p>\n<h2>Aramaic</h2>\n<h3>Aramaic in the OT</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs18:26\">2KI 18:26</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa36:11\">ISA 36:11</a> <em>Aramaic is a language related to Hebrew, known from Assyrian times. Under the influence of the Persian empire Aramaic was the diplomatic language in later OT times. In Palestine, by the time of the NT, it was spoken widely, having largely displaced Hebrew as the everyday language of the Jews.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra4:7\">EZR 4:7</a> <em>The text of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra4:8-Ezra6:18\">Ezr 4:8–6:18</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:12-Ezra7:26\">7:12–26</a> is in Aramaic</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer10:11\">JER 10:11</a> <em>The text of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer10:11\">Jer 10:11</a> is in Aramaic</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan2:4\">DAN 2:4</a> <em>The text of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan2:4-Dan7:28\">Da 2:4–7:28</a> is in Aramaic.</em></p>\n<h3>By NT times Aramaic had become the common language of Palestinian Jews</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John20:16\">JHN 20:16</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John5:2\">JHN 5:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:13\">JHN 19:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:17\">JHN 19:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:20\">JHN 19:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:40-Acts22:2\">ACT 21:40–22:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts26:14\">ACT 26:14</a></p>\n<h3>Aramaic expressions found in the NT</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt27:46\">MAT 27:46</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark15:34\">MRK 15:34</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:22\">MAT 5:22</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark5:41\">MRK 5:41</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark7:34\">MRK 7:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:36\">MRK 14:36</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John20:16\">JHN 20:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:15\">ROM 8:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor16:22\">1CO 16:22</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal4:6\">GAL 4:6</a></p>\n<h2>Hebrew</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs18:26\">2KI 18:26</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa36:11\">ISA 36:11</a> <em>Hebrew was the language of Israel in the period of the OT. By the time of the NT, it had been partially displaced in everyday use by Aramaic.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs18:28\">2KI 18:28</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr32:18\">2CH 32:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa36:13\">ISA 36:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:11\">REV 9:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev16:16\">REV 16:16</a></p>\n<h2>Greek</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:20\">JHN 19:20</a></strong> <em>Greek was the major cultural and commercial language of the eastern Mediterranean world. The NT was written in this language, ensuring the rapid spread of the gospel in this region.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:37-Acts21:39\">ACT 21:37–21:39</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:11\">REV 9:11</a></p>",
